{"timestamp": "2025-12-07 06:18:07.009603", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nOverview\\n- Topology: 2 hosts (pc_0_0, pc_0_1) each connected to a leaf; leaves connect to two spines; spines connect to a super-spine. All interconnects use EBGP (FRR) over /31 links. Hosts are on /24 subnets: 10.0.0.0/24 (pc_0_0) and 10.0.1.0/24 (pc_0_1).\\n- Goal: Assess network health, identify any anomalies, localize faulty devices, and determine root cause.\\n\\nFindings\\n\\n1) Anomaly Detection (Reachability/Packet Loss)\\n- pc_0_1 exhibits severe packet loss even to its local default gateway:\\n  - From pc_0_1 to leaf_router_0_1 (10.0.1.1): 75% loss (4 sent, 1 received).\\n  - From leaf_router_0_1 to pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2): 40–50% loss across repeated tests.\\n- End-to-end between hosts is impacted:\\n  - pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1 pings timed out due to excessive loss on pc_0_1’s side.\\n  - pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0 showed 75% loss.\\n- pc_0_0 and its leaf are normal:\\n  - pc_0_0 -> default gateway (10.0.0.1): 0% loss.\\n  - leaf_router_0_0 -> pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2): 0% loss.\\n\\n2) Control Plane and Routing Health (No Fabric-Wide Issue)\\n- BGP sessions across all layers are established and stable:\\n  - leaf_router_0_0 and leaf_router_0_1: Peers up with expected neighbors, PfxRcd values populated.\\n  - spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1: Peers up with super-spine and leaves, PfxRcd populated.\\n  - super_spine_router_0: Dozens of peers established, stable counters.\\n- Leaf routing tables fully populated with all expected /24 host networks and connected /31s (via EBGP). No missing routes or anomalies.\\n- This indicates the Clos fabric control plane and routing are healthy. The problem is localized to the edge facing pc_0_1.\\n\\n3) Localization of Faulty Device/Domain\\n- The loss occurs even on the local LAN between pc_0_1 and its leaf (10.0.1.1), strongly localizing the issue to the host or its directly attached link.\\n- ARP/neighbor on leaf_router_0_1: 10.0.1.2 in “DELAY” state intermittently, consistent with unreliable L2/L3 connectivity to the host.\\n- pc_0_0 and leaf_router_0_0 side are clean, further isolating fault to the pc_0_1 domain.\\n\\n4) Root Cause Identification\\n- Traffic control configuration on pc_0_1’s interface is injecting packet corruption:\\n  - On pc_0_1 eth0: qdisc netem root corrupt 60%.\\n  - tc stats: “qdisc netem … corrupt 60%” present; packets sent align with current activity.\\n- On pc_0_0 eth0: default fq_codel qdisc (no impairment).\\n- The 60% packet corruption on pc_0_1 eth0 explains:\\n  - High packet loss both to its gateway and to/from other hosts.\\n  - Intermittent success for some pings (e.g., 25–60% success) depending on corruption hit/miss.\\n- No evidence of link errors, misrouted traffic, or BGP/routing issues elsewhere in the fabric.\\n\\nConclusions\\n\\n- Anomaly: Yes. Severe packet loss affecting pc_0_1 connectivity, including to its local default gateway.\\n- Fault Localization: Edge host pc_0_1’s NIC path (eth0) or host configuration; the rest of the fabric (leaves, spines, super-spine) appears healthy.\\n- Root Cause: Deliberate traffic impairment on pc_0_1 via tc netem configured with “corrupt 60%” on eth0, causing widespread packet corruption and resultant loss. Control plane and routing are normal; the data-plane impairment is confined to pc_0_1’s interface.\\n\\nEvidence Highlights\\n- pc_0_1 -> 10.0.1.1: 75% loss; leaf_router_0_1 -> 10.0.1.2: 40–50% loss.\\n- pc_0_0 -> 10.0.0.1 and leaf_router_0_0 -> 10.0.0.2: 0% loss.\\n- leaf_router_0_1: ip neigh shows 10.0.1.2 in DELAY state intermittently.\\n- pc_0_1 eth0: “qdisc netem … corrupt 60%”.\\n- BGP summaries across leaves/spines/super-spine: all neighbors established; routing tables fully populated.\\n\\nNo remediation is provided at this stage per request., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='f03c0b31-52e4-46c7-b598-61a3fb9977a4'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
